      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A fixed-rate mortgage offers the same monthly payment for the life of the loan, while an adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) has an initial period with a lower rate that adjusts based on market indexes after that window. If you're looking at a 5-year window, your payments could change significantly depending on how much the interest rate index rises during those five years. For example, if rates increase by 1%, your monthly payment might rise by roughly 0.3% to 0.5% of the loan amount, or more if the rate hike is larger. This variability means that while ARMs offer lower initial payments, they carry the risk of higher payments if rates climb unexpectedly during your 5-year horizon.",
